<br>
They are dead handy for monks, and now also rogues, given the FD-esque nature of Escape. ^_^<br>
<br>
They're also considerably handy for normal exp grouping; most exp groups don't require a cleric, but it's convenient to have a res available if something should go wrong!<br>
<br>
The procedure for recharging items is:<br>
<br>
• Find a vendor that still has a visible “hole” in his inventory, so that if you sell something then it immediately appears in his “for sale” window.<br>
<br>
• Sell the fully-charged item to the vendor, so that it appears in the trade window.<br>
<br>
• Sell all of the items that you'd like to recharge.  It can be just one, or it can be several.  They add to the stack of the item in the merchant's window, but they all take the attribute for number-of-remaining-charges from the first one that you sold.<br>
<br>
• Buy all of the items back.  They will all now be charged to that number of charges which the very first item contained.<br>
<br>
<br>
Popular items to recharge include:<br>
<br>
• Res sticks (1,000pp per res, approximately);<br>
<br>
• Vials of Shrieker Essence, for shrinking (20pp);<br>
<br>
• Cazic-Thule's puppet strings, for charming (a few thousand) - use these to get yourself an Overthere Hammer!  Porting to the Overthere is very convenient for reaching Charasis; it saves a run across Skyfire; ^_^<br>
<br>
• Snare glands (negligable cost) - frequently used by melee classes to increase their aggro on a target.<br>
<br>
Generally speaking, alchemical potions are too costly to buy back; moreso than the cost of just making another.<br>
